  "body": "Currently cloud providers in kubernetes handle the stopping of an instance differently.\r\n\r\nAt a minimum aws, openstack, vsphere, ovirt, and rackspace handle a stopped instance by removing that cloud node from kubernetes.  When the instance starts again it re-registers with kubernetes and is available for scheduling.\r\n\r\nOther cloud providers, including GCE, do not delete the cloud node from kubernetes when the instance is stopped.  Instead the node stays in kubernetes and ends up marked NotReady.  When the instance is started again it sends a status update and is marked Ready.  The node isn't removed from kubernetes unless the instance is deleted from the cloud provider.\r\n\r\nHow a stopped instance is handled should be consistent across cloud providers.  How should a stopped instance be handled?  Should it be deleted from kubernetes or should it stay and be marked NotReady?  Should the behavior be determined by a config knob that would all the user to determine the action across all cloud providers?\r\n\r\n@kubernetes/sig-aws-misc @kubernetes/sig-openstack-pr-reviews @simon3z @jbeda @thockin @thommay @abithap @dagnello @justinsb @smarterclayton @ncdc ",
